<p><i><b>The God of Small Things</b></i> (1997) is a politically charged novel by Indian author <a href="/wiki/Arundhati_Roy" title="Arundhati Roy">Arundhati Roy</a>. It is a story about the childhood experiences of a pair of <a href="/wiki/Fraternal_twins" title="Fraternal twins" class="mw-redirect">fraternal twins</a> who become victims of circumstance. The book is a description of how the small things in life build up, translate into people's behavior and affect their lives. The book won the <a href="/wiki/Booker_Prize" title="Booker Prize" class="mw-redirect">Booker Prize</a> in 1997.</p>
<p><i>The God of Small Things</i> is Roy's first book, and as of 2009<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_God_of_Small_Things&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_God_of_Small_Things&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow">[update]</a></sup>, is her only novel. Completed in 1996, the book took four years to write. The potential of the story was first recognized by <a href="/wiki/Pankaj_Mishra" title="Pankaj Mishra">Pankaj Mishra</a>, an editor with <a href="/wiki/HarperCollins" title="HarperCollins">HarperCollins</a>, who sent it to three British publishers. Roy received half-a-million <a href="/wiki/Pound_sterling" title="Pound sterling">pounds</a> (approx. $970,000 <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">USD</a>) in advances, and rights to the book were sold in 21 countries.</p>
